[1]
Date: Sat, 23 Aug 1997 11:33:48 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Paul D. Millikin" <millikin@mtco.com>

As a people pathologist, I'm very curious about the nature of the sores
that Pfiesteria causes on fish and possibly on humans. I understand that
in it's dinoflagellate form it secretes the toxins that kill the fish, but
at some point it changes to an ameboid form that causes the sores.
I'd like to know whether that's true or not, but am more curious about
whether either form is confined to the skin or might be invasive. Could
one of the little beasties invade the blood stream and eat up some internal
organs? The liver, maybe?
If there are fish pathologists around, I'd very much appreciate it if you
could steer me in that direction somehow.

Paul D. Millikin, MD
Dep't of Patholgy
UICOMP (Univ. of Illinois College of Medicine at Peoria)
"Paul D. Millikin" <millikin@mtco.com>
